text.tspan: 6.2MONITORING OF VESSEL CONDITION AND LEGAL COMPLIANCE6.2.1VESSEL INSPECTION REPORT (VIR)In order to assess the condition of the vessels and to ascertain whether the maintenance, HSEQA and training standards are in linewith regulatory and Company requirements, a Superintendent shall inspect each vessel at intervals of about 4 months but notexceeding 6 months.Note: Company representatives (possessing sufficient marine technical knowledge and background to properly evaluate and advisevessel personnel) should try to make a short voyage on the vessel at least annually, and should observe and advise the company ofany required safety improvements and corrective actions.When a vessel under goes Dry-Docking the vessel's condition is assessed prior docking and deficiencies are attended to during the docking. A detailed dry docking report is alsoprepared by the Technical Superintendent. As such the Dry Docking Report is to be considered as equivalent to a Superintendent Vessel Inspection as stipulated above.Deviation from the above to vesselâ€™s schedule or other operational reasons requires approval from the General Manager.During his stay on board the Superintendent shall:1) Carry out a random physical examination of documents and machinery to verify that maintenance has been properly carried out.2) Hold a formal safety meeting with crew and officers and include any feedback obtained in the visit report.3) Identify and report any near misses, unsafe acts or conditions.4) Identify and report any Best Practices.5) Follow up on any matters from Technical, Operations, HSEQA, Crew and Accounts Departments.Subsequent to his visit the Superintendent shall:a) Make out a detailed inspection, report in the Company's stipulated form "Vessel Inspection Report - AI1" highlighting all deficiencies andareas, which require attention. This shall include details of present condition, action required and due date.b) Ascertain with the vessel if necessary resources such as material, tools, manpower and time are available to undertake the designated jobs.c) Hand over copies of this inspection report to the Master and Chief Engineer.d) Submit the report to the General Manager for review.e) Upload the report in the Phoenix system.f) Monitor that the completion of tasks has been updated in the Phoenix system by the Master/ Chief Engineer.g) Verify during the next visit whether the vessel has correctly undertaken the remedial actions.6.2.2ADDITIONAL RESOURCES AND OVERSIGHT FOR OLDER VESSELSThe company recognizes that additional oversight and resources are required for vessels whose age is greater than 15 years (oldervessels) and provides for the following:a) A greater annual Environmental Budget.b) Reduced interval between Superintendent Inspections from 4 months to 3 months.c) The Dry Docking Module in Phoenix contains requirements to be complied with by all vessels during Dry Docking. This includesspecific requirements for vessels whose age is greater than 10 years and 15 years.6.2.3INSPECTION OF TANKS AND VOID SPACESInspection of tanks and void spaces is to be carried out as per the procedures laid out in Section 33 of the Vessel OperationsManual (VOM).These reports enumerating the condition of the tank coating and the internal structures shall be scrutinized for re-coating/ passivationof tanks. An action plan shall be formulated for onboard repairs. The owners shall be accordingly informed and the ship staff and/or a repairteam shall take remedial actions as required. The Technical Superintendent shall do verification of the jobs carried out. In case major steel renewal is required, such jobs shall, asfar as practicable be carried out during the routine docking of the vessel.6.2.4VESSEL PERFORMANCE REPORTSOn the basis of the Technical and Operational reports, the vessels' performance shall be monitored, and advised to take appropriatecorrective actions. In case of large deviation from norms, such as increase in fuel consumption and reduction in speed, an underwaterinspection shall be carried out and, subject to the Owners approval, cleaning of the hull or the propeller shall be carried out.6.2.5LUBRICATING OIL SAMPLESLub. oil samples for the main equipment shall be landed for analysis as per Vessel Operations Manual Section 37and these reportsshall be reviewed against the previous reports to ascertain if there is any deterioration in the quality. Depending on the results,appropriate corrective actions shall be suggested to the vessels.6.2.6MEGGER TEST REPORTSOn the basis of the quarterly megger test reports, an assessment of the condition of the electrical equipment shall be made.
